        <!-- Project Overview -->
        <div class="project-section">
            <h3>Project Overview</h3>
            <p>
                This project demonstrates building <strong>secure private connectivity between two VPCs</strong> using 
                <strong>VPC Peering</strong>, enabling applications in one VPC to access resources in another without internet exposure.
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Created a <strong>VPC Peering connection</strong> between Lab VPC (10.0.0.0/16) and Shared VPC (10.5.0.0/16).</li>
                <li>Updated <strong>route tables</strong> in both VPCs to route peered traffic.</li>
                <li>Configured the <strong>inventory application</strong> to connect to the private database.</li>
                <li>Verified <strong>private connectivity</strong> without internet gateways.</li>
                <li>Analyzed <strong>VPC Flow Logs</strong> in CloudWatch to monitor traffic.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Architecture -->
        <div class="project-section alt-bg">
            <h3>Architecture Explanation</h3>
            <p>VPC Peering enables private communication between VPCs:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Lab VPC (10.0.0.0/16)</strong> – Hosts the inventory application on EC2.</li>
                <li><strong>Shared VPC (10.5.0.0/16)</strong> – Hosts the private database (no internet gateway).</li>
                <li><strong>VPC Peering Connection (Lab-Peer)</strong> – Private link between the two VPCs.</li>
                <li><strong>Lab Route Table</strong> – Routes 10.5.0.0/16 traffic through peering connection.</li>
                <li><strong>Shared Route Table</strong> – Routes 10.0.0.0/16 traffic through peering connection.</li>
                <li><strong>Security Groups</strong> – Allow port 3306 (MySQL) between peered VPCs.</li>
                <li><strong>VPC Flow Logs</strong> – Capture and monitor all network traffic.</li>
                <li><strong>CloudWatch</strong> – Visualize and analyze flow logs for troubleshooting.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Implementation Steps -->
        <div class="project-section">
            <h3>Implementation Steps</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Step 1:</strong> Created VPC Peering connection between Lab VPC and Shared VPC.</li>
                <li><strong>Step 2:</strong> Accepted the peering connection in Shared VPC.</li>
                <li><strong>Step 3:</strong> Updated Lab VPC route table: 10.5.0.0/16 → Lab-Peer.</li>
                <li><strong>Step 4:</strong> Updated Shared VPC route table: 10.0.0.0/16 → Lab-Peer.</li>
                <li><strong>Step 5:</strong> Configured security groups to allow MySQL (port 3306) traffic.</li>
                <li><strong>Step 6:</strong> Tested inventory app connection to private database.</li>
                <li><strong>Step 7:</strong> Enabled VPC Flow Logs on both VPCs.</li>
                <li><strong>Step 8:</strong> Analyzed flow logs in CloudWatch to verify traffic patterns.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Key Learnings -->
        <div class="project-section alt-bg">
            <h3>Key Learnings</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Created <strong>VPC Peering connections</strong> for inter-VPC communication.</li>
                <li>Configured <strong>route tables</strong> to enable peered traffic routing.</li>
                <li>Understood <strong>CIDR block routing</strong> and route table priorities.</li>
                <li>Enabled <strong>private connectivity</strong> without internet gateways or NAT.</li>
                <li>Used <strong>VPC Flow Logs</strong> for network traffic visibility.</li>
                <li>Analyzed logs in <strong>CloudWatch</strong> for troubleshooting.</li>
                <li>Verified <strong>port-level connectivity</strong> (MySQL on 3306).</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Best Practices -->
        <div class="project-section">
            <h3>Notes & Best Practices</h3>
            <p>
                VPC Peering is ideal for multi-VPC architectures:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Use <strong>VPC Peering</strong> for direct private connectivity between VPCs.</li>
                <li>Consider <strong>AWS Transit Gateway</strong> for complex multi-VPC setups.</li>
                <li>Always <strong>update route tables</strong> in both VPCs for bidirectional traffic.</li>
                <li>Use <strong>security groups</strong> to restrict traffic to specific ports.</li>
                <li>Enable <strong>VPC Flow Logs</strong> for monitoring and troubleshooting.</li>
                <li>Avoid <strong>overlapping CIDR blocks</strong> between peered VPCs.</li>
                <li>Use <strong>DNS resolution</strong> across peered VPCs for easier connectivity.</li>
                <li>Monitor <strong>peering connection status</strong> regularly.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

